shared_text:
Scott County, Kansas - Department of Emergency Management
August 23 at 9:43 PM ·

As we prepare to send them back to school, here's a reminder about crosswalk safety. It's EVERYONE'S responsibility.

✅ Talk to your children about using crosswalks, making eye contact with drivers, cross/don't cross signals, etc.

✅ Talk with your young drivers to ensure they're aware of the laws, tips for ensuring pedestrian safety, and to drop the distractions

✅ Remind yourself to ditch the distractions, that no deadline or errand is worth the rush to prevent you from looking twice at crosswalks and intersections, and always yield to pedestrians (even if they're in the wrong)

USD 466 School Health
August 20 at 4:13 PM ·

‼️Attention parents‼️We need your help! We need your help to do a quick check of your children before sending them to school everyday. We want to ensure that every one arrives at school healthy and ready to learn! Please, take a look at the attached picture for symptoms to look for and instructions. Any children that arrive with signs or symptoms that look like COVID (and aren’t caused by other conditions) and/or may have been exposed may be sent home for evaluation.

Teachers and student are considered Essential Workers. See the attached picture that describes the process that we will follow in the case of an exposed teacher or student without symptoms. We will of course ultimately follow the directions provided to us by the Health Department. You can also click the link for the complete KDHE guidance @ https://www.coronavirus.kdheks.gov/DocumentCenter/View/1377/Guidance-for-Modified-Quarantine-in-K-12-Schools---7-28-2020

Parents,
If you have a student who has their iPad at home this summer, please remind them to get their iPads charging NOW. It is important for students to charge and power-on their iPads. A device that has been sitting dead may not function properly once turned on. It would be very much appreciated by our technology department if these issues can be addressed prior to school starting. An overwhelming number of iPad issues the first week of school will result in a longer wait to get your student's issues resolved. So, please help us out by simply powering up those iPads!

Student-Athletes & Parents,

Friendly reminder that all 7th & 8th Grade student-athletes need to take this baseline concussion test. The baseline test helps medical professionals treat individuals who are recovering from a concussion. This year we have joined teams with a new program called XLNTbrain in the fight against concussion injuries in sports.

This test can be taken from the convenience of your home, but will NOT work on an iPad. The instructions are provided on the document I've shared with you.

https://docs.google.com/document/d/1z0fjixawo-4T68BnFt4zPIUCknXq_mY7s3EpOuq7ehw/edit?usp=sharing

If you have any questions, you can direct them to myself or Leslie O'keson at leslieokeson@centura.org

We will be providing on site testing on the following dates, if you would prefer that:

August 5th & 6th @ SCMS
8:00am - 8th Grade Boys
9:00am - 8th Grade Girls
10:00am - 7th Grade Boys
11:00am - 7th Grade Girls

Thank you for your help in keeping our student-athletes safe!

post_text:
Uncertain what school fees you are to pay....hopefully this helps!
3rd-8th graders will pay the iPad fee (this needs paid by first day of school)
3rd-8th graders will pay the curriculum fee
6th-8th graders will pay elective fees (based on their schedule)
6th-8th graders will pay for PE uniform, if they don’t have one already

Couple notes:
3rd & 4th will NOT need an iPad cover, one will be provided.
5th graders will get the 7th generation IPad & WILL need a cover. You can purchase anywhere or from the school.
Student schedules will not be available for viewing (on GoEdustar) until a later date in August. Please note that elective fees can be paid at any time throughout the school year (so please don’t stress).
Make sure your student has their locker lock on the first day of school. Replacement locks are $5.

Fees can be paid online at www.ezschoolpay.com, thru the SCMS office, or mailed to 809 W 9th Street.
Please note our office is closed until Aug. 3rd.

SCMS Baseline Concussion Testing

Student-Athletes & Parents,

Each year we like to have our 7th & 8th Grade student-athletes take a baseline concussion test that can help medical professionals treat individuals who are recovering from a concussion. This year we have joined teams with a new program called XLNTbrain in the fight against concussion injuries in sports.

This test can be taken from the convenience of your home, but will NOT work on an iPad. The instructions are provided on the document I've shared with you.

https://docs.google.com/document/d/1z0fjixawo-4T68BnFt4zPIUCknXq_mY7s3EpOuq7ehw/edit?usp=sharing

If you have any questions, you can direct them to myself or Leslie O'keson at leslieokeson@centura.org

We will be providing on site testing on the following dates, if you would prefer that:

August 5th & 6th @ SCMS
8:00am - 8th Grade Boys
9:00am - 8th Grade Girls
10:00am - 7th Grade Boys
11:00am - 7th Grade Girls

Thank you for your help in keeping our student-athletes safe!

8th graders and parents!

We are just as anxious and excited for softball/baseball to get started as all of you. Registrations are open at www.scottrec.org! Grades are for the 2019-20 school year.
-Practices will begin June 1.
-Games will begin June 15.

We added two new leagues this summer, 7th/8th Change Up League and 9th-12th Slap League. Both these leagues are coed slow pitch softball. These leagues you will be able make your own team (12 on roster) but still have to register as an individual participant. Please email team roster to kylie@scottrec.org!

Our office remains closed until May 18 so online registration is highly encouraged!

post_text:
Scott City Community,

Following our Easter weekend I think it is important to make sure we have our priorities in line and that students are NOT overwhelmed during this time. The following are the KSDE recommendations for MAXIMUM student commitment each day:

Pre-K: 30 mins
Grades K-1: 45 mins
Grades: 2-3: 60 mins
Grades: 4-5: 90 mins
Grades: 6-12: 30 mins per teacher (3hr Max)

The goal for this time is continuous learning. I believe we are accomplishing that. Make sure we are still taking advantage of this slower pace, more time together with family, and all of the learning opportunities around the house.

If your child is feeling overwhelmed please have them contact one of their teachers or administration. We would be happy to visit with them and ease any anxieties.

Have a great week and as always Go Beavers!

#BetterTogether
#GrowthOverGrades
#SCoverCovid
#WeAreSC

“Check in with the Counselors”

We would like to offer K-8th grade students the opportunity to participate in group Zoom meetings with the counselors and their peers. These weekly meetings will be a time for checking in, staying connected with others, and group discussion.

Meetings will likely take place at 1:00 pm on a weekday. If this is something your student is interested in, please email us so we can begin organizing these online meetings. After we get a head count we will have more specific information (day of the week, how to log on, etc.) As this is a different format for student groups than what we are used to, please be patient with us.

Please remind your student in any group format there is no absolute guarantee of privacy, please consider this when sharing information in any online group.

This new Home Court ap is awesome! All you ballers out there should take advantage during this time. You just need to download the free ap on your phone or iPad(IPad works better because of the bigger screen)
It is important to crossover and touch the dot with your hand. This helps work both hands and it forces players to keep their eyes up because they have to keep their eyes on the screen. There are other drills, competitions, and workouts as well! Give it a shot!

SCMS Parents,
Please know we are doing our best, with the guidance of the State, to plan for continuous education for all of our SC kids. Administration has been meeting this week and will put plans in place with teachers next week. Each SCMS student will be contacted by their homeroom or IPS teacher via phone next week. Plans for virtual education will be in place by March 30. Teachers are missing their kids as much as kids are starting to miss school. We are blessed with some incredible educators at SCMS who will no doubt plan top-notch opportunities for our students, even if they cannot meet face-to-face. Our office and the school building will be closed next week, only staff will be intermittently permitted in. We know there are lots of questions and needs to be addressed. Please be patient with us as we work out the details through next week.

The letter below from Mr. Rumford contains goals and additional information as we move forward.

Thank you all for your words of encouragement and understanding during this time. WE ARE SC!! #bettertogether

The CDC report indicates flu rates are on the way up this flu season. The current increase is similar to the flu season of 2017-2018.
It is not too late to get your vaccine. Ask your regular health care provider or the Scott County Health Department to schedule an appointment for your flu vaccine.

The CDC recommendations to avoid influenza is to:

1. Get your flu shot.

2. Try to avoid close contact with sick people.
While sick, limit contact with others as much as possible to keep from infecting them.
If you are sick with flu-like illness, CDC recommends that you stay home for at least 24 hours after your fever is gone except to get medical care or for other necessities. (Your fever should…

shared_text:
Niki Gleason Depperschmidt uploaded a file in the group: USD 466 School Health.
December 5, 2019 at 9:39 AM ·

Just a reminder as we are beginning flu season-

Updated (10/23/2019) Information on K.A.R. 28-1-6 in regards to Influenza:

If you recall from last school year, the Kansas Department of Health and Environment stated that a student diagnosed with influenza had to be out of school for 7 days after the onset of illness.

A memorandum has been issued from KDHE today changing this to 5 days after the onset of illness. The student must also still be 24 hours fever free without the aid of medication.

If your child has been diagnosed or suspected of having influenza then subsequently started on an anti-viral medication (such as Tamiflu) please notify the school. If you have questions, please call Niki Depperschmidt, RN at the school health office 872-7660.

The Scott County School District was made aware of a threat to the HS over the weekend. Through this investigation with Law Enforcement we found no credible threat to our students or the school. As a precaution, Law Enforcement will be present in the schools as they frequently are to ensure the safety of the students and staff.

Scott County Schools takes the safety of students and staff seriously, and we appreciate the assistance of our our local PD in this endeavor.

If you have any questions please contact the high school or district office.

post_text: Scott City Middle School is looking for a qualified applicant to work in the front office. This person must have proficient computer skills and enjoying working with kids, parents, and staff. All applicants should be organized, punctual, flexible, have a welcoming demeanor, and willingness to multi-task. Job duties will include a wide range of office managerial skills, interacting with students and visitors to SCMS, and prepping for school events. Bilingual communication skills are a huge plus, but not required. To apply, please pick up an application at the SCMS office.

post_text: Here are some answers to frequent questions we are getting about the first day of school at SCMS. The time constraints of new construction will not allow for us to host an open house prior to the start of school. Please trust that when you drop your child off on the first day that they will be in great hands and we will get everyone where they need to be. The building is new to ALL students, new and returning. So nerves the first day are to be expected. We are excited for everyone to get a chance to see the building! You will see on the schedule for the first day that parents are invited for lunch with their student on the first day to tour the building. Things are looking great in the building and we can't wait to start another great school year very soon!

post_text: Scott City Middle School is looking for an individual interested in working with ESL and at-risk youth as a paraprofessional in our Enrichment and Intervention program. Job duties would include working one-on-one assisting students with their academics, as well as assisting classroom teachers with groups of students. A willingness to learn, punctuality, flexibility, and dependability are a must! This position would begin the last week of August and will follow the school calendar. Applications can be picked up at the district office, 704 S College.
